# AGENT CORE PRACTICES

## 9. Use Cases Documented Before Code

Each use case has:
- **Actor** — who executes
- **Preconditions** — what must be true before
- **Main flow** — happy path step by step
- **Alternative flows** — variations and exceptions
- **Applied rules** — which BRs are verified
- **Events fired** — what happens after execution

A use case that is not documented must not be implemented.

## 10. Explicit API Contracts

- Every API has explicit versioning from day one (`/v1/`, `/v2/`).
- Authentication and tenant identification are mandatory on every request.
- Error responses follow a single structured pattern (never random strings).
- Pagination, sorting, and filters follow uniform conventions.
- Endpoints reflect the domain — not the database. Resources are named by business concept.

## 11. Security as Requirement, Not Feature

- Strong authentication (MFA) for elevated-privilege roles.
- Session TTL defined per role — admin sessions expire faster.
- Rate limiting per user and per IP on every public API.
- Sensitive data encrypted at rest and in transit.
- All external communication uses TLS. No exceptions.
- Data legislation compliance (LGPD, GDPR) is a functional requirement from day one.

## 12. Test-Driven Development (TDD)

```
E2E (5%)          → end-to-end complete flows
Integration (20%) → use cases + infrastructure
Unit (75%)        → domain layer (entities, rules, state machines)
```

- Domain tests are written **before** implementation.
- Standard test format: GIVEN / WHEN / THEN.
- Minimum Domain Layer coverage: 90%+.
- A test must fail for exactly one reason.
- Tests do not depend on real database, network, or filesystem.

## 13. AI / Agent Integration

When the system integrates LLMs or AI agents:
- AI operates **within** the Application Layer — never accesses Domain or Infrastructure directly.
- AI only reads data. Never writes directly to the database.
- Every AI suggestion requires human confirmation before persisting.
- Agent access is restricted to minimum necessary (least privilege).
- Every LLM call is logged: input, output, model, timestamp, user who triggered it.
- AI responses are always marked as suggestions — never as definitive truth.
- Personal and sensitive data is never sent to the LLM.

## 14. Minimum Project Glossary

Every project maintains a glossary with domain terms in `docs/glossary.md`.
- Business terms and precise definitions
- Enums and their possible values
- Acronyms and abbreviations used in code

Code that uses a domain term uses **exactly** the same name from the glossary — no creative translations, abbreviations, or synonyms.

## New Project Checklist

Before writing the first line of code, verify:
- [ ] Layers defined and responsibilities documented
- [ ] Main entities and aggregates identified
- [ ] Value Objects listed with invariants
- [ ] Business rules written in GIVEN/WHEN/THEN format
- [ ] State machines documented with valid transitions
- [ ] Access roles and permission matrix defined
- [ ] Domain events cataloged
- [ ] Use cases documented with actor, flow, and preconditions
- [ ] API contract sketched
- [ ] Domain glossary exists

If any item is blank, the agent must ask before implementing — never assume.
